sentences.sentence: UNODC established One-Stop Women and Juvenile Facilitation Center in Gujranwala!

11 Jan 2023, Gujranwala - The UNODC Country Office in Pakistan opens a Women & Juvenile Facilitation Center (W&JFC) in Gujranwala in collaboration with Punjab Police, with the financial support of the Government of Norway.
The Women and Juvenile Facilitation Centre (WJFC) is the second facility of its kind established by UNODC in Punjab after successful operations of its forerunner Centre in Gujrat since 2019.

The WJFC is modelled as per international standards, providing comprehensive services and compassionate environment to women and juvenile victims of violence for reporting, recording and investigation of crimes.
In order to officially operationalize the Center, an inauguration ceremony was held at Saddar Police Station, Gujranwala today.

Officials from the Royal Embassy of Norway, H.E Per Albert Ilsaas, Ambassador of Norway to Pakistan; Anja Myrtveit, Second Secretary Development Program; Per Martin Bjartan, Police Liaison Officer; Bilal Majeed, Program Advisor Development and Dr. Jeremy Milsom, Representative, UNODC Country Office Pakistan along with many senior official from UNODC and Police Department attended the ceremony hosted by the Police Administration Gujranwala.

The inauguration of the WJFC marked an important milestone as part of a multi-year Government of Norway funded program “Enhanced Capacity of Criminal Justice Actors in Punjab” implemented by UNODC in collaboration with the Government of Punjab.

The Program aimed to improve the organizational response of Criminal Justice Institutions toward the victims of crimes and violence and ensure better justice outcome, particularly in the cases of violence against women, girls, and juvenile.

Mr. Munir Ahmad Marath, Regional Police Officer Gujranwala, welcomed the guests and extended gratitude to UNODC (COPAK) and Government of Norway for its gracious support and appreciated the Centre as a historic move in Gujranwala region towards protecting the vulnerable victims in need of help.
